body:
@hachikuji I suggest creating a new PR for the `ConcurrentLinkedQueue` version. It's worth keeping the `Vector` version in this branch for future archeology.

I think we should merge one of the options to trunk (leaning towards the `ConcurrentLinkedQueue` version atm). I am less sure about `0.10.1.1` since I'm generally conservative about bug fix releases and prefer to give non trivial PRs some time to bake, but it does fix an important bug so it may be worth backporting to 0.10.1 as well.

It's worth running the system tests on the branch.

@guozhangwang Any news about `punctuate` updates?

I'd like perform an action in my processor at least every x time units, even if no data arrives. This is necessary when I use processing time and the events I receive are sparse, but the results must be responsive.

Since I'm using processing time, I expected to have `punctuate` running every x time units, independent on the incoming streams. The [docs](http://docs.confluent.io/3.1.0/streams/developer-guide.html#defining-a-stream-processor) are a bit ambiguous in my opinion as they say: "For example, if processing-time is used as the record timestamp, then punctuate() will be triggered every specified period of time". Also, the multiple calls to `punctuate` when an event arrives after a time of inactivity seem strange when using processing time, since they all have the same timestamp parameter.

@dpoldrugo - I wonder if we can simulate this without having to start up a full kafka streams topology? 
i.e., we have `StreamThreadTest`, which i know is a bit hard to follow, but it allows us to manually trigger the rebalance, and to manually set up the tasks. So we could have a test where we call `rebalanceListener.onPartitionsAssigned(assignedPartitions);` - we overload `StreamThread.createStreamTask` to create a task with a simple topology that just has a single state store, and we overload the `commitOffsets` method of the Task to throw the `CommitFailedException`. Keep a reference to the `StateStore` for validation
Then we invoke `rebalanceListener.onPartitionsRevoked(...)` which will cause the task to throw the exception. We then need to check that we get the `CommitFailedException` and we should also check that the store is actually closed, i.e., by calling `stateStore.isOpen(..)` and checking that it returns false or by calling `stateStore.get("key")` and checking that it throws an `InvalidStateStoreException`
